{"_id":"6825cab0-4661-11e9-8eaa-bf9870a70db5","postId":"2009_05_detection-of-half-open-dropped-f127b1d1-2c83-3dd0-9e4b-214360c6e878","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2009/05/detection-of-half-open-dropped.html","replyTo":"f5ab7240-4607-11e9-8eaa-bf9870a70db5","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"I assume you mean the receive timeout.\r\n\r\nIn a half-open connection situation, the receive timeout would cancel reads after the given time. However, [`SO_RCVTIMEO` is not respected by all implementations](https://linux.die.net/man/3/setsockopt), and [on Windows, it only affects *blocking* reads](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/desktop/winsock/sol-socket-socket-options) (which you shouldn't be using in production code anyway).","date":"2019-03-14T13:59:39.105Z"}